#Time Series¶

A time series is a sequence of data points collected or recorded at regular time intervals (daily, monthly, yearly, etc.).

  • Formally: Y={y1​,y2​,y3​,…,yt​}
  • where each yt is an observation at time 𝑡.

##Time Series data: Time series data is data that is collected, recorded, or observed at regular time intervals (seconds, minutes, days, months, years, etc.).

Patterns:

  • Trend → long-term movement.
  • Seasonality → repeating cycle.
  • Cyclic behavior → irregular long-term oscillations.
  • Noise → random fluctuations.

Examples

  • Daily closing price of a stock.
  • Monthly rainfall in a city.

##Cross Sectional Data: Cross-sectional data is data collected at a single point in time (or over a very short period) across multiple subjects such as individuals, companies, countries, etc.

👉 Unlike time series, cross-sectional data does not track changes over time — it’s more like a snapshot.

Examples

  • A survey of income levels of 1,000 households in January 2025.
  • The GDP of 50 countries in 2024.

##Pooled Data: Pooled data is the combination of both time series data and cross sectional data.

Why is pooled data useful?

  • More information → It contains both time and entity variation.
  • Better analysis → Allows us to study how variables change over time and how they differ across entities.
  • Econometrics & Machine Learning → Panel regression, Random Effects, Fixed Effects models rely on pooled data.

1. Stationary Time Series¶

A time series is stationary if its statistical properties (mean, variance, autocorrelation) do not change over time.

Properties:

  • Constant mean (does not drift up or down).
  • Constant variance (no increasing spread).
  • Autocorrelation depends only on lag, not on time.

👉 In other words: The series looks statistically the same at all points in time.

2. Non-Stationary Time Series¶

A time series is non-stationary if its statistical properties change over time.

Signs of Non-Stationarity:

  • Trend: mean increases or decreases over time.
  • Changing variance: volatility increases/decreases.
  • Seasonality: repeating patterns over fixed periods.

Example:

  • Airline passengers data (trend ↑ + seasonality).
  • Stock prices (variance changes over time).

Why Stationarity is Needed

Most time series models assume constant mean, variance, and autocorrelation.

  • Non-stationary data → spurious results.
  • Stationary data → models can learn meaningful patterns.

Methods to Make a Time Series Stationary:

A. Differencing

  • Subtract the previous value from the current value to remove trends:
  • Can do first-order differencing (lag 1) or second-order if needed.
  • Removes linear trends.

B. Log Transformation

  • Stabilizes variance if the series grows exponentially.

C. Detrending

  • Fit a trend line (linear, polynomial, or moving average) and subtract it:

D. Deseasonalizing

  • Remove seasonal component (from decomposition)

E. Combination

  • Sometimes you need log + differencing or detrending + deseasonalizing to make it fully stationary.

Decomposition of a time series¶

Decomposition in time series means breaking down a time series into its underlying components to better understand its structure.

A typical time series is assumed to have 3 main components:

  • Trend (T) → Long-term movement (upward, downward, flat).
  • Seasonality (S) → Repeating short-term patterns (daily, weekly, yearly cycles).
  • Residual/Noise (R) → Irregular, random fluctuations that can’t be explained by trend/seasonality.

🔹 Two Types of Decomposition

1. Additive Model

  • Y(t)=T(t)+S(t)+R(t)
  • Seasonal variation is constant in size.
  • Example: Monthly ice cream sales increase by about +200 units every summer, regardless of overall sales growth.

2. Multiplicative Model

  • Y(t)=T(t)×S(t)×R(t)
  • Seasonal variation scales with the trend.
  • Example: Airline passengers — as the total number of passengers grows, the seasonal peaks and dips also get larger in absolute terms.
In [44]:
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose
from dateutil.parser import parse

# Multiplicative Decomposition
multiplicative_decomposition= seasonal_decompose(df['Number of Passengers'], model='multiplicative', period=30)

# Additive Decomposition
additive_decomposition= seasonal_decompose(df['Number of Passengers'], model='additive', period=30)

# Plot
plt.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize': (16,12)})
multiplicative_decomposition.plot().suptitle('Multiplicative Decomposition', fontsize=16)
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])

additive_decomposition.plot().suptitle('Additive Decomposition', fontsize=16)
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])

White Noise¶

In time series, white noise is a sequence of random values that:

  • Have zero mean (average ≈ 0).
  • Have constant variance (homoscedasticity).
  • Have no autocorrelation (values are independent across time).

In short we can say: White noise is a completely random series with no pattern. It’s used as the baseline to check whether your time series model has captured all useful information.

Detrend a Time Series¶

Detrending a time series means removing the long-term trend component from the data, so that only the short-term variations (seasonality + residuals) remain.

Mathematically:

  • If a time series is: Y(t)=T(t)+S(t)+R(t)
  • then detrending removes T(t): Y′(t)=Y(t)−T(t)

🔹 Why do we detrend?

  • Stationarity requirement → Many time series models (like ARIMA) assume the series is stationary (no trend/constant mean).
  • Focus on seasonality/irregularities → Helps analyze cycles and seasonal effects without trend bias.
  • Comparisons → Makes it easier to compare multiple series that grow at different rates.
In [49]:

Deseasonalize a time series¶

Deseasonalizing (or deseasonalization) a time series means removing the seasonal component so that we can study the underlying trend and residuals more clearly.

  • If a time series is: Y(t)=T(t)+S(t)+R(t)(Additive model) or Y(t)=T(t)×S(t)×R(t)(Multiplicative model).
  • then deseasonalizing removes S(t).

Why do we deseasonalize?

  • To study the true trend without seasonal fluctuations.
  • To make comparisons across periods.
  • To prepare data for forecasting models that require stationary input (like ARIMA).
  • To analyze cyclic or irregular movements without seasonal bias.

Methods of Deseasonalization

1. Additive Model:--

  • Deseasonalized Value=Y(t)−S(t)

2. Multiplicative Model

  • Deseasonalized Value=Y(t) / S(t)

👉 Choice depends on whether seasonality is constant (additive) or proportional to trend (multiplicative).​

In [51]:
# Deseasonalize a time series
deseasonalized=df['Number of Passengers'].values / result_mul.seasonal
plt.plot(deseasonalized)
plt.title("Air Passengers Deseasonalied", fontsize=14)
plt.show()

Autocorrelaation and Partial Autocorrelation Function¶

ACF measures how much current values depend on past values at different lags

PACF measures the “direct” correlation at lag k, without indirect effects from shorter lags.

Lag:

In time series, a lag means shifting the data back by a certain number of time steps.

  • Lag 1 → yesterday’s value (previous time step)
  • Lag 2 → value from 2 days ago
  • Lag k → value from k time steps earlier
In [54]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import acf, pacf
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf

plot_pacf(df['Number of Passengers'].to_list(),lags=50, ax=axes[1])

Granger Causality Test¶

Granger causality tests whether past values of one time series improve the prediction of another, beyond what its own past values explain.

In [57]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import grangercausalitytests
data= pd.read_csv("dataset.txt")
data['date']= pd.to_datetime(data['date'])
data['month']=data.date.dt.month
grangercausalitytests(data[['value', 'month']], maxlag=2)
